            "id": 1,
            "uuid": "blog-001-nextjs-performance",
            "title": "Optimizing Next.js Applications for Maximum Performance",
            "slug": "optimizing-nextjs-performance",
            "content": "<p>Performance is crucial for modern web applications. In this comprehensive guide, I'll share the techniques I've learned while building high-traffic Next.js applications.</p><h2>1. Image Optimization</h2><p>Next.js provides built-in image optimization through the Image component. Always use it instead of regular img tags:</p><pre><code>import Image from 'next/image'\n\nexport function Hero() {\n  return (\n    &lt;Image\n      src=\"/hero.jpg\"\n      alt=\"Hero image\"\n      width={1200}\n      height={600}\n      priority\n    /&gt;\n  )\n}</code></pre><h2>2. Code Splitting</h2><p>Leverage dynamic imports to reduce initial bundle size...</p><h2>3. Server Components</h2><p>With Next.js 14's App Router, Server Components are the default. This means less JavaScript sent to the client...</p><h2>Conclusion</h2><p>By implementing these optimizations, we achieved a 40% improvement in Lighthouse scores and significantly better user experience.</p>",
            "excerpt": "Learn how to optimize your Next.js applications for maximum performance with image optimization, code splitting, and Server Components.",
            "image_url": "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1555066931-4365d14bab8c?w=800&h=400&fit=crop",
            "published": true,
            "published_at": "2024-02-15T10:00:00Z",
            "views_count": 2450,
            "likes_count": 128,
            "reading_time": 8,
